CMD
0 Adds a new note to the system.
1 Searches for notes that satisfy all specified filters. If none are provided, all notes are selected.
2 Applies the given filters to the current selection. If the selection is empty when running the command, the result acts as a find command.
3 Shows the content of the current filter, where all notes in the filter are combined to the output.
4 Adds a data folder for the current selection.
5 Shows details about the current selection.
6 Shows the tags of the current selection (or all notes in the selection is empty).
7 Ends the program.
8 Creates a new mode, which controlls the default behaviour of the program.
9 Deletes an existing mode.
10 Edits an existing mode.
11 Activate an existing mode.
12 Deactivate an existing mode.
13 Shows an overview of all existing modes.
14 Updates the statistics of the program, note that on Windows this is done automatically after a file inside the Files folder is edited. 
15 Open all notes in the selection.
16 Show the help.
17 Show all todos that are defined in the notes by the TODO marking.
PA
0 Date argument, can be in the format of DD.MM.YYYY or DD.MM, where the year is the current year, or DD, where the month and the year are the current years. Additionally, the characters t (for today) and y (for yesterday) can be used.
1 Tags argument. This can be a list of tags, which are separated by whitespaces.
2 The name of a mode.
3 The name of a command.
OA
0 Option that controlls whether only notes with data folders should be considered or whether to create a data folder.
1 Dates are expected.
2 Filter for notes that contain at least one of the tags.
3 Filter for notes that contain all of the given tags.
4 Filter for notes that do not contain any of the given tags.
5 Uses a regular expression to filter for notes where at least one of the tags matches the regular expression.
6 Uses a regular expression to filter for notes where the regular expression matches the note's content.
7 Filters for notes with the given versions
8 Option to show tags.
9 Option to show the metadata (tags, filename, ...)
10 Option to create and show a table-of-content. 
11 Option to hide the note date in the output.
12 Option to automatically open image data.
13 Use the html format to show the result (only if pandoc is installed). 
14 Use latexs tex format to show the result (only if pandoc is installed).
15 Use the pdf format to show the result (only if pandoc is installed and latex is installed and working)
16 Use words docx format to show the result (only if pandoc is installed).
17 Use markdown format to show the result.
18 Show the relative file path.
19 Show the absolute file path.
20 Show the last modified information.
21 Show the note content.
22 Add options to the specified mode.
23 Remove options from the specified mode.
24 Add tags to the specified mode.
25 Remove tags from the specified mode.
26 Change the mode name.
27 Whitespace separated list of tags, which will be stripped of access whitespaces, commas and converted to lower case characters.
28 A range of dates, given as start_date end_date or start_date-end_date, where the dates can be in the format DD.MM.YYYY, DD.MM or DD. Additionally, t (today) and y (yesterday) can be used.
29 A regular expression given as text.
30 A list of versions, where each version is separated by a whitespace.
31 A mode name as text.
32 The name of a command.
33 Mode option to show tags.
34 Mode option to show metadata for the show command.
35 Mode option to create and show a table of content for the show command.
36 Mode option to hide the date in the show command.
37 Mode option to open image data in the show command.
38 Mode option to use html format.
39 Mode option to use tex format.
40 Mode option to use pdf format.
41 Mode option to use docx format.
42 Mode option to use md format.
43 Mode option to show the relative note path.
44 Mode option to show the absolute note path.
45 Mode option to show the last modified information.
46 Mode option to show the note content.
47 Adds a folder watcher.
48 Removes a folder watcher.
49 Specify a path to the folder that should be watched, followed by the corresponding tags for that folder, separated by whitespaces (the list of tags separated with whitespaces as well).
50 Specifies a path to a watch folder.